video docs are a WIP

The safest way to embed videos using custom modules is to use a rich text field.

I discourage using their HubL or JS outside of the rich text field.

To do anything crazy yet. The code is in flux still, If it’s used in the rich text fields however it makes it easy for HS to change the code needed to make it work, without breaking anything.

That said you may be able to make the video appear in a lightbox by having the lightbox’s window actually be a div on the page already - and simply hide and show the div. that way you’re not moving the player, or relying on code that could change and break.

The devs I’ve talked to about it said they are working on the docs and they are working to finalize the js and hubl used for it - seemed like it’d maybe be a few months out.

That said I’d approach it the way I noted above, to reduce the likelyhood you have to rekajigger some modules and stuff down the road
We are just working on handling one parameter without you having to specify it. Will post in here when the documentation is public

So this is whats going on with the above (large videos in Safari)^^

Safari must have somewhat recently adjusted or changed how large of a video file it is willing to consume on the client side. The reason cdn2 links work is because on cdn2 we respond to these requests with a `206` (<https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Status/206>), and specify a `Content-Range` http header to allow Safari to only download partial content. We are investigating being able to do the same on connected domain requests actively. I will update with any progress we make on doing this in production

At this point I can just remake the modules content with the cloned copy. It’s pretty simple.
We’re trying a couple things to see if we can get your copy to link up with the pages.
Ok. Yes please try that. The new module’s called “2018SW - Image and Text wextras”.
Can you check again? Should be working now.
THANK YOU
Can you shed a little light on what the issue was? Reverting to a DM1 revision was a mistake. I don’t want to repeat this mistake again.

There’s a difference in how we reference modules in v1 vs v2, name vs id. Somehow during upgrade, the legacy name was not set on the new module which broke it in the editors. We were able to just manually set the old legacy name on the copy of the module to fix it. Still not sure how you lost your module though. We’re just going to block reverting to v1 to be safe.
Ok. Yeah there was a “/” in the old module. Thanks again.

Just a clarification. This was not fixed by renaming the file, there’s a legacy name property that can’t be set by the front end that needed to be set. So I think you should be fine to rename the module if you want.
